***Version One***
Version one is code designed to work as a single button for every single image that is used. You can find the code in:
Thumbnails.js

As you can see its a nightmare to look at, but the top part is simplified version and cleaner.
Thats what every single image would look like with its own button.

In Index.html, it pulls Thumbnail.js after it bulls script.js.

***Version Two***
Bassically, version two utilizes a list of images, and builds a button in initilization for each image. 

You can find the Version Two files here:
imagelist.js – Contains a simple array of image file names.
thumbnail_list.js – Uses that list to automatically generate the clickable thumbnails and link or run code based on which image is clicked.
Version Two only needs the image names. The code builds all buttons in the browser.

The Advantage with Version Two, is if you need to add additional images, you can add the image name to imagelist.js and the code will still automatically build a button for it.

The disavantage with this version, is eventually the code will need to be updated so that each will run its own code and/or open up to its own links.
However! The list still provides a cleaner approach and also allows easier integration of more images (even possibly allowing USACE to add images and videos themselves for the future for longevity purposes)''
Also helps with scalebility 
  
The structure in index.html remains mostly the same, it just loads imagelist.js first, followed by thumbnail_list.js, replacing the older thumbnails.js from Version One.
